<h2>Delaware Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Delaware offers a comprehensive array of incentives and rebates that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) allows homeowners to deduct 30% of the cost of installing a solar energy system from their federal taxes through 2032. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work. There are no caps on the credit amount, and unused credits can be rolled over to future tax years.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available through 2032, this credit covers solar panels, inverters, mounting equipment, wiring, and installation costs. The credit steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations.</li>
<li><strong>Delaware Green Energy Program:</strong> Provides grants up to \$4,500 for solar installations on residential properties, with additional funding available for low-to-moderate income households. The program also offers rebates for energy storage systems and electric vehicle charging stations.</li>
<li><strong>Delmarva Power Rebates:</strong> The utility offers rebates up to \$750 for high-efficiency HVAC systems, \$200-400 for programmable thermostats, and additional incentives for home energy audits and weatherization improvements.</li>
<li><strong>Net Metering:</strong> Delaware's net metering program allows solar system owners to receive full retail credit for excess electricity fed back into the grid, effectively using the grid as a battery for surplus solar production.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Solar energy systems are exempt from property taxes in Delaware, meaning the added home value from solar installation won't increase property tax bills.</li>
</ul>

